:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF041365%2F1"><gtr:id>9A80543B-06B7-4BCC-AC50-B9E26255F44F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Social Contract, Deliberative Democracy and Public Policy</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F041365/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>In the understanding of social and political values, two powerful images play a role in our political culture.&amp;nbsp; The first is that of justice as a social contract.&amp;nbsp; According to this image, just institutions should embody agreement on terms of social co-operation among citizens under conditions of fair negotiation.&amp;nbsp; The second image is that of deliberative democracy.&amp;nbsp; According to this image public policy should be determined through processes of public reasoning satisfying conditions of equality and openness by citizens or their representatives. Both ideas assert that justifiable policies are ones that, under appropriate conditions, would secure assent by the members of society.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />Professor Weale firstly plans to bring together the understanding of these two sets of ideas. He will then interpret these ideas in the light of the notion of a property-owning democracy, a political system in which there is widespread private ownership of the means of production but democratic co-operation on matters of public interest.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The research will test these ideas using applications to current public policy issues. 
&lt;br /></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>113771</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>This award was continued at UCL when I moved there in 2010. The findings informed the continuation of the work that I undertook at UCL, which led to the development of a user template for social values in health policy.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2010</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>145531DE-8456-4F28-B3D9-346C56ADD3DB</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>546b86bb585331.28678273</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Healthcare</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The award was continued at UCL and so the key findings are the same as those reported under that grant, as follows: 

? Social contract theory provides a coherent and plausible interpretation of social justice and deliberative democracy when formulated in terms of the 'empirical method'. The empirical method involves looking at forms of social organisation that approximate the circumstances of justice.

? The analysis of common pool resource regimes provides us with models that can be used in such an empirical approach.

? This analysis shows us both how producers can acquire the right to the full fruits of their labour within socially agreed constraints.

? The analysis also shows the requirement of a deliberative rationality that is defeasible, this last property being closely linked to requirements of deliberative democracy.

? Redistribution is justified as a measure to even out income fluctuations across the life-cycle and in response to events that cannot be anticipated at the individual level.

? Contrary to some dominants claims in the literature on social justice, social contract theory supports a political theory of the welfare state (understood broadly as the European social model) as much, or more, than is supports a political theory of the property-owning democracy.

? In particular fields of public policy the policy paradigm supported by this approach is distinctive. For example, in priority-setting in healthcare, it supports a social insurance approach - broadly conceived - more nearly than a rights approach or a maximising cost-effectiveness approach.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>In scientific terms, there will be an issue of Political Studies Review devoted to a symposium on the book that is the principal outcome of the research.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>CD1AEE50-6477-4FB9-BBAF-33DB6BF01BF5</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>546b8d4c0692a2.79883320</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Environment,Healthcare,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.ucl.ac.uk/spp/people/albert-weale</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>288E1C4F-7D1E-4BDB-BF53-D7875548739D</gtr:id><gtr:title>Legitimacy and political contracting in the EU</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/62b0ee05a3145f4daec3c828aa786de7"><gtr:id>62b0ee05a3145f4daec3c828aa786de7</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Albert Weale (Author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_148966460513c3f2ea</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>D766B3EE-EA2A-4183-A4B2-C75781F5F12D</gtr:id><gtr:title>Social contracts and democratic deliberation</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/62b0ee05a3145f4daec3c828aa786de7"><gtr:id>62b0ee05a3145f4daec3c828aa786de7</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Albert Weale (Author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_599528162613c3f600</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gt